The area

Address
Neighborhood: Trevi
A non-stop photo and souvenir opportunity, Trevi is all about action. From early morning through the wee hours, the piazza surrounding Trevi Fountain hosts a never-ending flow of tourists hoping to make a wish or take a selfie. Clever restaurants, charming gelaterias, uncanny bars, kitsch shops, and a range of hotels make up the local landscape. Beneath the bustle are the remains of an ancient neighborhood that you can visit by heading over to a repertoire cinema and asking for a peek underground. There is something for everyone, but if peace and quiet are what you seek, plan to visit in the early morning hours.
How to get there
  • Barberini - Fontana di Trevi 7 min walk
  • Spagna 8 min walk

  • Jim W.
    Atlanta, Georgia1,350 contributions
    An obligatory stop in Rome
    From a tourist perspective, this seems almost an obligatory stop on the Rome itinerary. We visited on our first afternoon, actually as our first stop after leaving the hotel. We were there in the early afternoon, probably at or before 1 p.m. on a Sunday. The light was still good for photos, with the faade behind the fountain in full sunlight. The fountain is located in a small plaza fed by multiple small streets. It opens up with some space on 3 sides of the fountain, with the 4th side bounded by a building full of sculptures from which the water flows. There are also sloped 'stadium' stone seating facing the fountain's pool. When we visited, the seating was almost fully occupied. A lot of people's aim seemed to be to get close to the pool in order do accomplish the traditional toss-a-coin-in thing. It appeared that you had to work your way down there, as there was a continual flow of people seeking to toss coins and take selfies. It was crowded enough up at the top rim of the seating along the streets. We opted to do our sightseeing and photos from up there and avoid additional crowding. I don't know what crowding is like at other times, or if there is any point where you can come here with less crowding. We didn't return during the remainder of our trip. Another point I'll make is that we were here in a less crowded time of year, so I can only imagine that crowds in July or August are even more impressive. The fountains are pretty and it is part of the Rome experience to stop by. Just don't expect a leisurely or relaxed visit.
    Visited November 2023
    Traveled with family

James S
Toronto, Canada2,067 contributions
Crowded And A Bit Disappointing
Oct 2024 Couples
Our first day in Rome was pretty well packed with sightseeing. After walking from the Basilica di Santa Maria to the Spanish Steps, we began heading back towards our hotel with a slight detour to take in one more attraction before calling it a day and grabbing some supper. That attraction was the Fontana di Trevi or Trevi Fountain.

The Trevi Fountain completed in 1762 is the largest Baroque Fountain in Rome and one of the most famous fountains in the world. A lot of this fame comes from its portrayal in movies and popular culture including Roman Holliday (1954) Three Coins in the Fountain (1954) and La Dolce Vita (1960).

The fountains original purpose was a terminus point for an Aqueduct bringing fresh water 13 kilometres outside the city built in 19 BC. While this Aqueduct still functions today it is no longer the main source of potable water for the city and the fountain has taken on a less functionary role. To that end in 1629 Pop Urban VIII finding the present fountains undramatic commissioned something more suitable for the area be constructed.

Perhaps due to its image in popular culture the fountain is seen as one of the more romantic spots in the Eternal City. To the extent there are even a group of Italian men who cruise the fountain daily hoping to pick up lonely and romantic female tourists. The locals even have an unflattering nickname for them. Thes would be Romeos aside the other major thing to watch out for are pickpockets and other petty thieves mainly due to the crowds.

Getting there from the Spanish steps was relatively easy. Once we reached Via del Tritone we just followed the signage and more importantly the ever-increasing crowds. Via Tritone is the closest major street and has buses on it as well as Barberini Metro Station which is the closest one to the fountain. The HOHO stop for Trevi Fountain is actually located here about a 10-minute walk away.

The fountain is located at Piazza di Trevi a small Piazza almost completely dominated by the fountain itself. The fountain fronts the Palazzo Poli and, on whose faade, you can see the famous statutes depicting the taming of the waters.

We were here in October 2024 and sadly the water has been turned off as part of an ongoing repair project for the upcoming 2025 celebrations in Rome. Basically, fabulous sculptures aside we were left looking at an empty pool.

Despite this the place was still overly crowded, with literally thousands of people jammed into a very small area. Theyre also not leaving quickly either. Most despite the lack of any water insisted on taking and posing for numerous selfies and tossing coins into the fountain which with the construction fencing ringing the site was actually a futile gesture.

The tradition of the coins is simple. If one throws a coin into the fountain, it means they will return to Rome sometime. Im not sure if this still applies if you toss it into the construction scaffolding. All the coins are collected and donated to charity.

The dense and unmoving crowds really sadly detract from experiencing the fountain to its fullest. One could try and gain a vantage point form the Hotel Fontana on the south side of the Piazza as it has a restaurant and bar but Im sure reservations are both required and hard to come by unless one is staying there. Benneton and other stores may also offer a viewpoint but again Im sure that theyre tired of tourists just coming in to see if they can see the fountain.

Somewhat disappointed on how our day had ended we left Piazza di Trevi we began walking back towards our hotel. Coins or not we knew wed be returning to Rome in the future.
Written November 6, 2024

A magnificent Roman landmark!
Dec 2023 Solo
The Trevi Fountain is certainly the most famous, the largest and most likely the most beautiful of all fountains in Rome. The current version of the fountain was built in the mid-18th century and it has become one of the iconic Roman landmarks. During most of the day and in the evening the fountain is surrounded by crowds of tourists, many of whom are keen to throw coins into the water. A total of over a million euros worth of coins is taken out of the fountain each year and donated to charity. Sadly, the fountain was recently cordoned off for restoration, so if you're eager to see it properly, you'll have to wait until 2025. The best time to explore this beautiful site is to go either very early in the morning or very late at night when there's only a handful of people around.

Cosmina Lavinia
111 contributions
Magical - A Must-See in Rome
Sep 2024 Family
The Trevi Fountain is a beautiful, iconic spot in Rome that you can easily pass by multiple times while exploring nearby attractionsits truly hard to miss! The fountain is free to visit, but be prepared for crowds at nearly any time of day (which we also encountered). For those looking for a unique photo perspective, theres a shop across from the fountain where you can go up to the first floor and take photos from above, giving a great view without the crowds.

If you plan to visit on a Monday morning, note that the fountain is usually drained for cleaning. We also heard that it may be closed at times for restoration in preparation for the Jubilee year, so checking the news or local updates can be helpful to avoid any surprises.

Overall, the Trevi Fountain is a must-see for its beauty and vibrant atmosphereit truly captures the magic of Rome!

P.S. And dont forget the tradition: toss a coin (or twoor three) into the fountain to ensure youll one day return to Rome!
